      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Solomon.—The emphatic word. (See 2Samuel 12:24.) The Hebrew is Shĕlōmō; for which the LXX. gives Sălōmōn; Syriac, Shĕleimûn; Arabic, Suleimân (same as “Solyman the Magnificent”). The original form of the word had the final n which we see in the cognate languages. The Assyrian Shalman (in Shalmaneser) and the Moabite Salamanu seem to be identical. The Vulg. has Pacificus (peace-maker). (Comp. the Greek Irenæeus, the German Friederich, our “Frederick,” peaceful.) Sŏlŏmon is the New Testament spelling.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Solomon.",
            "children": []
