  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 9.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Shall be born",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is not the necessary translation of the verb. The form ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "נולָד",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " does not express here future time. Solomon was already born when the word of the Lord came to David. On the other hand, we may suppose special emphasis to belong to the clause, His name shall be Solomon. The name designates the man ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "of peace",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the clause is an announcement, probably intended to throw further into the shade the alternative name ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Jedidiah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which also had been divinely given (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 12:24, 25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
